8. Student Roles and Training
- Undergraduate students:
 • Assist with survey administration, participant recruitment, scheduling, and study visits.
 • Help with data entry, basic data analysis, and literature searches.
 • Present posters and talks at research symposia and conferences.
- Graduate students and coordinators:
 • Take lead roles in designing studies, managing datasets, supervising RAs, and writing manus
cripts.
- Training Emphasis:
 • Ethical research conduct (e.g., informed consent, confidentiality).
 • Cultural competence when working with Black and minoritized participants.
 • Strong quantitative and scientific-writing skills.
9. Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) for a PNIRD Chatbot
Q1. What does “PNIRD” stand for?
A. PNIRD stands for Psychoneuroimmunology of Risk and Disease Laboratory.
Q2. Where is the PNIRD Lab located?
A. The lab is housed at Virginia State University in the Department of Psychology in Virginia,
USA.
Q3. What are the main topics PNIRD studies?
A. PNIRD focuses on substance use (especially cannabis), stress, mood, cardiovascular function,
 neurocognition, and immune markers in Black and other underserved populations.
Q4. What kinds of participants does PNIRD usually recruit?
A. Many PNIRD studies recruit Black college students at HBCUs and Black community members, incl
uding people living with HIV, depending on the project.
Q5. Does cannabis always harm the immune system?
A. PNIRD research suggests that the relationship between cannabis and immune markers is complex
. In some studies, cannabis users had higher immune cell counts than non-users. The lab is stil
l investigating what this means for overall health.
Q6. What is heart-rate variability (HRV) and why does it matter?
A. HRV is a measure of beat-to-beat variation in heart rate. It is used to understand how the a
utonomic nervous system responds to stress and rest. PNIRD uses HRV to study how autonomic bala
nce relates to cognitive performance and mental health.
Q7. How can students get involved with PNIRD?
A. Interested students can contact the lab’s email or lab director, ask about open research ass
istant positions, and share their interests in topics like substance use, mental health, and he
alth disparities.
